# Avoid Regular Expressions

Do not use regular expressions (`re`, `re.compile`, etc.) for parsing user queries, workflow inputs, or other natural-language text.

Prefer structured parsing instead: tool arguments, `json.loads`, `ast.literal_eval`, digit checks, and delimiter-based splitting (`"-"`, whitespace).

Do not scan free-form text for arbitrary words or phrases (e.g. `"unit"`, `"forecast"`, `"inventory"`). That is brittle and no better than regex. Only match specific words when the vocabulary is truly fixed and closed — month names, ISO date parts, enum values defined by the domain.

## Examples

```python
# ❌ BAD — regex for query parsing
FORECAST_UNITS = re.compile(r"\b(\d[\d,]*)\s+units?\b", re.IGNORECASE)

# ❌ BAD — scanning free-form text for arbitrary words
def _parse_forecast_units(content: str) -> int | None:
    lowered = content.lower()
    for suffix in ("units", "unit"):
        position = lowered.find(suffix)
        # ... scan backwards for digits

# ✅ GOOD — accept structured tool arguments (year, month, forecast_units)
def update_sales_forecast(
    product_name: str,
    year: int | str | None,
    month: str | int | None,
    forecast_units: int,
) -> str:
    ...

# ✅ GOOD — fixed vocabulary lookup (months) plus structural formats (digits, YYYY-MM)
MONTH_ALIASES = {"jan": 1, "january": 1, ...}

def _parse_month_number(month: str | int | None) -> int | None:
    if isinstance(month, int):
        return month if 1 <= month <= 12 else None
    text = str(month).strip()
    if text.isdigit():
        number = int(text)
        return number if 1 <= number <= 12 else None
    key = text.lower()
    if key in MONTH_ALIASES:
        return MONTH_ALIASES[key]
    return None
```
